<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Schweinfurth</emphasis>
1739, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Ryding</emphasis>
1116); Yemen (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Spellenberg</emphasis>
5426); Saudi Arabia (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Collenette</emphasis>
5367); Nigeria (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Lely</emphasis>
362).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="77" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
The type of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Schimper</emphasis>
660) has leaves with a relatively broad central lobe 5-10 mm wide and this is matched in South African material (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Dieterlen</emphasis>
97a has even wider leaves) but narrower lobes are much more common in southern Africa. Plants towards the northern end of the range have few-flowered cymes, quite frequently reduced to single flowers. They are often more strongly pubescent and with less pronounced, often simple basal auricles whereas bifurcate auricles are the norm further south. Examples of this northern form include 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Simwanda</emphasis>
108 from Zimbabwe, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Robinson</emphasis>
8 from Zambia, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Symoens</emphasis>
13595 from Congo, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Eggeling</emphasis>
2593 from Uganda, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Bally</emphasis>
5592 from Kenya, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Newbould</emphasis>
774 from Somalia, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Scott Jones</emphasis>
32 from Eritrea, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Wood</emphasis>
3281 from Yemen and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Collenette</emphasis>
5367 from Saudi Arabia,
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<pageBreakToken pageId="77" pageNumber="78" start="start">Convolvulus</pageBreakToken>
aschersonii
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the leaf shape and the short pubescence. The central leaf lobe is entire and often very narrow, most notably in specimens from Namibia. Possible hybrids or intermediates with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with strongly sinuate leaf lobes occur quite frequently in Transvaal but are hardly known elsewhere. (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Hanekom</emphasis>
2528, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Meeuse</emphasis>
9020, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Frieberberg</emphasis>
3195, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Wilms</emphasis>
983, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Mogg</emphasis>
12299, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Acocks</emphasis>
2169, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Marais</emphasis>
36). From 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sagittatus" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus sagittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baker, Bull Misc. Inform. Kew 1894: 67. 1894. (Baker" authorityYear="1894" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus thomsonii" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="thomsonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus thomsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the usually 2-5-flowered peduncles, bifurcate auricles and corolla less than twice as long as the calyx, rarely exceeding 12 mm in length. Intermediates or possibly hybrids with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sagittatus" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus sagittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occur in South Africa, (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Baur</emphasis>
350, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Galpin</emphasis>
1037, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Wilms</emphasis>
2158, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Meeuse</emphasis>
10253, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Pillans</emphasis>
5605), Zimbabwe (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Eyles</emphasis>
8473) and Zambia (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Best</emphasis>
107). These have larger flowers than typical of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the peduncles are 2-flowered and the leaves like those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These were, at least mostly, treated as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sagittatus subsp. var. var. linearifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="sagittatus" subSpecies="var." variety="linearifolius">Convolvulus sagittatus subsp. grandiflorus var. linearifolius</taxonomicName>
&quot; by 
<bibRefCitation author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="641 - 792" refId="B225" refString="Meeuse, ADL, 1958 1957. The South African Convolvulaceae. Bothalia 6: 641 - 792" title="The South African Convolvulaceae." volume="6" year="1958">Meeuse (1958</bibRefCitation>
: 683).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
